Launched in December 2021, JWST is designed to observe the universe in infrared light, allowing it to see some of the most distant and oldest objects in the universe.

Some of the recent images from JWST have been truly breathtaking. For example, the telescope has captured stunning views of the Carina Nebula, a massive star-forming region in our Milky Way galaxy. The images reveal intricate details of the nebula's structure, including towering pillars of dust and gas where new stars are being born.

JWST has also observed some of the most distant galaxies ever seen, providing astronomers with valuable insights into the early universe. One of the most remarkable discoveries so far is the identification of a galaxy called GLASS-z13, which is estimated to be about 13.5 billion years old. This means that the light we see from this galaxy has been traveling through space for almost the entire history of the universe.
